[![](img/woodwell_github.png)](https://github.com/whrc "Woodwell's github org")

## With Git we can

- Easily share code and analysis results with colleagues and supervisor  
- Track changes in the source code or files, and use this as a progress checker or management tool  
- Enable collaboration between peers (non-linear development)
- Genuinely make open science  

## Before going over the live demo...

Follow the instructions on [GitHub Docs](https://docs.github.com/en):  
1. [Create a GitHub account](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/signing-up-for-github/signing-up-for-a-new-github-account).  
2. [Download Git](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/quickstart/set-up-git).  
3. Set a [SSH connection](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/connecting-to-github-with-ssh/about-ssh) between your computer and GitHub.    
4. Use Git + GitHub, the most common commands are described in:  
  - [Get started | Using Git | About Git](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/using-git/about-git)

